<Document>
<name>Death Valley Crossing</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Death Valley Crossing</h2><p><i>Nevada / California, USA · Beatty NV to Panamint Springs CA via Furnace Creek</i></p><p><b>Drive from desert mountains down to the lowest point in North America and back up.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>210 km (131 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>5–6 hrs with stops</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>November–March (summer is genuinely lethal — over 50 °C)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Extreme heat, no cell, flash flooding, fuel only at Furnace Creek and Stovepipe Wells, vehicles overheating on climbs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>301</td></tr></table><hr><p>Death Valley earned its name in 1849 when a wagon train of '49ers got lost in it for weeks. They left it saying 'goodbye, Death Valley' — only one had actually died. The valley contains the lowest point in North America (Badwater at 86 m below sea level), some of the hottest air ever recorded on Earth (56.7 °C, 1913), and yet wildflower super-blooms after wet winters. This route crosses the valley from Nevada in the east to the Panamint Range in the west, with a detour to Badwater. Drive in winter. Bring water you cannot drink in a day.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Zabriskie Point</b> — Eroded badlands of golden mudstone — 5-million-year-old lake-bed sediment. Sunrise here is one of the desert's great experiences.</li><li><b>Badwater Basin</b> — −86 m. Lowest point in North America. Walk the salt-crystal hexagons; look up at the cliff for the SEA LEVEL sign 86 m above your head.</li><li><b>Devil's Golf Course</b> — Crystallized salt eroded into jagged spires you can hear quietly cracking in the heat.</li><li><b>Artists Palette</b> — Volcanic ash beds oxidized into pink, green, yellow, lavender. One-way 14 km loop drive (no RVs).</li><li><b>Salt Creek</b> — A spring-fed stream supports endemic pupfish — survivors of an Ice Age lake, evolved to tolerate water saltier than the ocean.</li><li><b>Mesquite Flat Dunes</b> — The classic Death Valley dunes — Star Wars filmed Tatooine scenes here. Best at sunrise or under a full moon.</li><li><b>Father Crowley overlook</b> — Look down 600 m into Rainbow Canyon — military jets often practice low passes through it. 'The Star Wars Canyon.'</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
